      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe slightly higher pKa₂ of alanine reflects the **electron-donating methyl group** on the α-carbon. The methyl substituent increases electron density at the nitrogen, making the –NH₃⁺ group slightly more reluctant to release a proton (i.e., a stronger base / weaker acid). This is a classic inductive effect: alkyl groups stabilize the conjugate base (–NH₂) relative to glycine's unsubstituted α-carbon.\n\nThe identical pKa₁ values suggest the methyl group has negligible influence on the distant carboxyl group's acidity — the inductive effect attenuates rapidly over two bonds.\n\nIn practical terms, both amino acids behave very similarly in aqueous solution and in metal coordination chemistry, which is consistent with the SRD-46 database showing both ligands binding a similar suite of metals (Cu²⁺, Ni²⁺, Zn²⁺, Co²⁺, etc.).\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
